      "content": "You are right to be concerned about bias, but the most accurate way to teach this is to present the \"living Constitution\" theory as the dominant legal interpretation that protects minority rights against majoritarian tyranny, while acknowledging the opposing \"originalist\" view that judges should strictly follow the text and let elected officials decide social issues. By framing the debate as a clash between protecting fundamental human rights versus strict adherence to democratic procedures, you allow students to see the complexity without imposing your own political stance. This approach empowers them to analyze the arguments themselves rather than memorizing a single perspective.",
